# Musician beat — the OODA cadence hook.
#
# Fired by the kernel beat scheduler on this context's wakeup cadence (the
# musician default is once per phrase, so phrases compose back-to-back and tile
# the line). `kj drive` publishes a turn request for the current context; the
# server's turn driver runs the model turn. Its ABC output is committed to the
# shared score on the beat, and MIDI is derived from that committed notation for
# playback — notation is the score, MIDI a render. This script is the
# user-editable seam — change the prompt, gate the drive, precompute facts here.
#
# The beat scheduler seeds this run with the transport report (KJ_-prefixed,
# matching the kernel-injection convention — cf. KJ_PARENT_BLOCK_COUNT):
#   $KJ_TICK         — the track's playhead tick (beat index, frozen off-beat)
#   $KJ_PHRASE       — phrases elapsed while playing
#   $KJ_TEMPO        — tempo in whole BPM
#   $KJ_PHRASE_BEATS — beats in one phrase window: the amount of music to compose
#                      this turn (the schedule lead is one phrase, so a turn's
#                      phrase tiles the next window). The fill target.
#   $KJ_HEARD        — JSON array of recent committed notation across tracks
#                      ([{tick, track, abc}, …], oldest→newest). The score blocks
#                      are hydration-silent, so this is the only way the player
#                      sees what was just played.
#   $KJ_PULSE        — per-attachment monotonic wakeup counter; reliable ordering
#   $KJ_EPOCH_NS     — wall-clock ns, shared across contexts woken the same beat
#
# PRECOMPUTE IN RC (a big win for rc as a feature): rather than make the model do
# bar arithmetic in its weights (error-prone, and a small model can't be handed a
# calculator tool without stalling — see issues.md "RO-kaish for players"), do the
# math here in kaish and hand the model spelled-out, exact fill targets. In 4/4 a
# beat is a quarter note, so bars = beats / 4.
bars=$(( KJ_PHRASE_BEATS / 4 ))
#
# `kj drive --prompt` writes the report as a real User block, so the model
# hydrates it as the fresh user turn (a cloud model REQUIRES a user message —
# Anthropic rejects a system-only turn). No positional context: the tick runs
# with this context current, so `kj drive` targets it.
kj drive --prompt "Transport: tick $KJ_TICK, phrase $KJ_PHRASE, $KJ_TEMPO BPM, 4/4 in C. Recently played (oldest→newest JSON): $KJ_HEARD. Play the NEXT phrase, continuing seamlessly from what you just played. Write exactly $KJ_PHRASE_BEATS quarter notes — ONE note per beat, 4 notes per bar, a barline | every 4 notes, $bars bars total — so the line is continuous with no gap. CRITICAL: with L:1/4 a bare note letter is exactly one beat (a quarter note); do NOT add duration numbers (no C2, no C/2) and do NOT pack multiple notes into a beat. Low register — use commas (C, G, A,). Output ONE complete ABC tune: X:1, then T:bass, M:4/4, L:1/4, K:C, then the body. Raw ABC only — no prose, no code fences."
